
===================================
📌 1. Finglish Version (Persian Latin Script)
===================================

📖 **Tashrih:**
    Dastoor `locale` baraye namayesh ya ta’yin zaban, mantagheh, va character encoding baraye barname-ha estefade mishavad. In dastoor barname-ha ra komak mikonad ta be dorosti matn-ha ra namayesh dahand va ba format-haye monaseb kar konand.

⚙️ **Gozine-ha:**
    🔹 `locale`  --> 🌍 Namayesh hameye etela'at locale jari.
    🔹 `locale -a`  --> 📝 Namayesh list-e hameye locale-haye nasb shode.
    🔹 `locale NAME` --> 🏷️ Namayesh faghat etela'at locale baraye `NAME` khass (masalan, `locale LC_TIME`).

🛠 **Mesal-ha:**

    $ locale

    🔹 Namayesh hameye taghirat locale jari.

    $ locale -a

    🔹 List-e hameye locale-haye dastras.

✅ **Mesal sade:**

    $ locale LC_MONETARY

    🔹 Namayesh format-e pool (currency) locale jari. Agar chizi namayesh dade nashavad, ya locale tayin nashode ya format-e pool dar locale jari tayin nashode ast.

===================================
📌 2. English Version
===================================

📖 **Description:**
    The `locale` command is used to display or set the language, region, and character encoding for programs.  This command helps programs to correctly display text and work with appropriate formats.

⚙️ **Options:**
    🔹 `locale`  --> 🌍 Show all current locale settings.
    🔹 `locale -a`  --> 📝 Show a list of all installed locales.
    🔹 `locale NAME` --> 🏷️ Show only the locale information for the specific `NAME` (e.g., `locale LC_TIME`).

🛠 **Examples:**

    $ locale

    🔹 Show all current locale settings.

    $ locale -a

    🔹 List all available locales.

✅ **Simple Example & Explanation:**

    $ locale LC_MONETARY

    🔹 Show the current locale's currency format. If nothing is displayed, either the locale is unset, or the currency format is not defined in the current locale.
